During the grant period, Drs. Robertson, Javan, and Cothran actively engaged in workshops, student-centered research, listening sessions, and regional and national Noyce meetings. This PI and Co-PIs focused on ways to strengthen ASUs current teacher preparation program, recruit and strengthen support for STEM Education majors, develop connections with community partners who have a vested interest in increasing the numbers of STEM teachers in the area, and refresh plans for a successful full-length Noyce Grant Program at Alabama State University.


On March 4th, 2023, and November 4th, 2023, Drs. Robertson, Javan and Cothran convened two Robert Noyce Program Workshops. The workshops were led by Dr. Robertson. While these workshops were free and open to the general public, the PI, co-PIs, and leadership team members from the Montgomery County Public School System (MCPSS), the Lowndes County Public School System (LCPSS), Trenholm State Community College, and Shelton State Community College participated. Virtual in format, the workshops featured keynote addresses and breakout sessions centered on several topics, including the following:


1.  The challenging SES landscape of the Black Belt region of Alabama;


2. STEM teacher shortages, recruitment, and retention in the state of Alabama;


3. Skills and knowledge that the MCPSS and the LCPSS need and want their new STEM teachers to have (onboarding);


4.  Strategies for passing the PRAXIS and edTPA;


5.  Challenges to recruiting and supporting STEM Education majors;


6.  A marketing and recruitment plan to recruit ASU STEM Education majors and STEM graduates from the area community colleges; and


7.  Ideal courses of study for community college students so that, after they graduate from the respective community college, they will be well-poised to major in STEM Education when they enroll at ASU


Over the course of the grant period, Dr. Javan co-authored published papers with students who were supported, at least in part, by this capacity building grant.


Over the course of the grant period, Dr. Cothran held listening sessions with current and former teacher prep candidates. Conversations were particularly eye opening and introduced several key foci for consideration in a future, full-length program (e.g., the attractiveness of teaching as a profession, mentoring and coaching, onboarding support, compassion-fatigue, self-care, developing socially just education practices, etc.). The student teachers and current teachers were eager to share their perspectives and suggestions. All expressed hopeful excitement about opportunities that could come from a future full-length Noyce grant.


